Player's Guide to Adventure in Skyrim
Welcome, traveler, to the frost-covered lands of Skyrim! You are about to embark on an adventure filled with ancient ruins, fearsome beasts, and untold treasures. This guide will provide you with the knowledge to forge your legend.

The Core Rule: The Roll of the Dice
This system is simple and relies on a single 20-sided die (d20). Everything you do, from swinging a battleaxe to persuading a Jarl, is resolved with a roll of the dice.
When you attempt an action where the outcome is uncertain, you will roll a d20. Your goal is to roll low.
Your Target Number
To succeed, you must roll equal to or under your relevant Stat Score. That Stat Score is your Target Number.
If you are trying to lift a heavy portcullis, you will roll against your Might.
If you are trying to disarm a trap, you will roll against your Agility.
If you are trying to identify a magic rune, you will roll against your Magic.
If you are trying to lie to a guard, you will roll against your Guile.
The Five Possible Outcomes
Every roll has five potential outcomes, ranging from spectacular success to disastrous failure. Let's look at each one.
Example In Action:
Let's say your character, a mighty warrior named Bjorn, has a Might score of 16. His Target Number for kicking down a door is 16. He rolls the d20...
Critical Success (A roll of 1)
The Result: You succeed brilliantly and gain an extra advantage. (x2 damage in combat)
Bjorn's Kick: He rolls a 1! The door doesn't just open; it flies off its hinges and smashes into a bandit on the other side, knocking them flat.

Clean Success (A roll that is UNDER your Target Number)
The Result: You succeed at your action without any negative side effects.
Bjorn's Kick: He rolls a 9 (which is under 16). With a satisfying crunch, the door splinters and swings open, clearing the way. Simple and effective.

Success with a Complication (A roll that is EXACTLY your Target Number)
The Result: You get what you want, but with a twist or a cost. The GM will introduce an unexpected complication.
Bjorn's Kick: He rolls a 16 (exactly his Might score). The door breaks open, but the noise is so loud that it alerts the entire dungeon to their presence. Or perhaps he succeeds, but the effort wrenches his shoulder, and he'll be at a disadvantage on his next physical action. "Yes, but..." is the rule here.

Simple Failure (A roll that is OVER your Target Number)
The Result: You fail to achieve your goal, but nothing catastrophic happens.
Bjorn's Kick: He rolls an 18 (which is over 16). His boot thuds solidly against the ancient oak, but the door holds firm. The attempt fails, and his turn might be wasted, but he's not in any worse of a position.

Critical Failure (A roll of 20)
The Result: You fail in the worst way possible, making the situation actively worse.
Bjorn's Kick: He rolls a 20! He puts all his might into the kick, but his foot slips on a loose stone. He stumbles, falls backward, and his trusty axe clatters loudly across the floor, sliding just out of his reach. He has failed, made noise, and lost his weapon.

