The Effect
When you Augment a spell, two things happen:
Pay the Cost: Consult the table above. Pay the Standard FP Cost of the Target Rank, plus an additional 1 FP per Rank increased. (e.g., Jumping 3 Ranks adds +3 FP to the cost).
Customization: For every Tier you jumped, you may apply one Augment from your known list.

The Augmentation Syllabus
Unlike standard spells which are bought with AP, Augments are principles of magical physics. You begin your journey knowing only the Fundamental Principle. To learn more, you must study at the College of Winterhold, find ancient Spell Tomes in dungeons, or be taught by a Master Wizard.
The Fundamental Principle (Known by All)
Amplify: Increase the primary numerical effect (Damage, Healing, or DR) by +3.
The Advanced Principles (Learned at the College)
Commonly taught to Apprentices and Adepts who study at Winterhold.
Extend: Increase the duration of the spell by +1 Round.
Reach: Increase the range of the spell by 30 feet. (Touch spells become Ranged).
Reinforce: Increase the HP of a Summoned Creature or Ward by +10.
The High Mysteries (Hidden Knowledge)
Found only in rare texts or taught by the highest ranking Wizards.
Pierce: The spell ignores 2 points of the enemy's Damage Reduction (DR).
Chain: The spell hits the primary target, then jumps to a second target within 10 feet for Half Effect.
Linger: The spell leaves a magical residue on the floor. Any creature entering the space takes 3 Damage (or Healing) per turn.
The Forbidden Physics (Legendary)
Secret techniques known only to Archmages, Dragon Priests, and Daedric Princes.
Dominate: The target suffers a -2 Penalty to their Resistance Roll.
Subtle: The spell makes no sound and has no travel time. It is undetectable until impact.
Lock: The spell physically binds the target. They are Slowed (Lose Minor Action) for 1 round.
Impact: The spell hits with kinetic force. The target is Pushed 5 feet away.


How to Play: The Adventure Begins
With your character forged, you are ready for adventure. Here are the core rules you'll need to know to survive the dangers of Skyrim.
Combat: Steel and Spells
Combat is fast, dangerous, and resolved in turns.
Turns: At the start of a fight, everyone rolls a d20. The highest roll goes first, continuing in descending order.
Actions: On your turn, you get one Major Action and one Minor Action.
Major Actions: Attacking an enemy, Casting a spell, Drinking a potion.
Minor Actions: Moving to a different location, Drawing a weapon, Bracing with a shield.
Bonus Actions: Some abilities live entirely outside your Major and Minor actions — reactions (Dragonskin, Frost Resistance), triggered abilities (Fighter's Rush, after taking damage), and any-time activations (Fleet Footed's Dodge). A Bonus Action consumes neither your Major nor your Minor Action, and it can be used even when it is NOT your turn. (Note for players arriving from D&D: this is not the D&D bonus action — in FROGS, the whole point of a Bonus Action is that it works off-turn.)
Free Actions: Cost nothing and consume no action slot, but happen on your own turn (e.g., a weapon's on-hit Soul Trap, applying poison with an Envenomed weapon).

Attacking & Damage
To attack, declare your target and roll against the relevant stat (Might for melee, Agility for bows). If you succeed, you deal damage. A weapon's damage is a fixed number listed in its description.
Defense: Staying Alive
Your primary defense is your armor, which provides Damage Reduction (DR). When you are hit by an attack, subtract your armor's DR from the incoming damage. DR is applied to each instance of Damage.
Example: A bandit hits you for 4 damage. You are wearing Steel Armor (DR 2), so you only lose 2 HP.
Shields
If you have a shield, you can use your Minor Action to brace.
Bracing: Reduce the damage of the next attack that hits you by an additional 2 points.
Standard Shield Stats: Damage Reduction 2.
Special Combat Actions
Beyond a simple attack, you can use your turn to perform a variety of special maneuvers. These are your keys to victory against tougher foes.
Cast a Spell (Major Action): Every spell has an FP cost. You must spend the FP and then succeed on a Magic roll to cast it.

Power Attack (Major Action): Before you roll a melee attack, you can spend 3 FP to add +2 damage if your attack hits. (Stackable)(Some perks can improve this).

Sunder Armor (Melee only)(Major Action): When facing a heavily armored foe, you can try to break their defenses. Make a MELEE attack roll against your Target Number. On a success, you deal no damage, but the target's DR is permanently reduced by 1. This can be done multiple times.
Critical Success (Roll of 1): You reduce the target's DR by 1 AND deal 1 damage.
Critical Failure (Roll of 20): You overextend and have Disadvantage on your next attack roll.
Durability & Repair
The reduction of Damage Reduction (DR) from a Sunder Armor action is permanent until the armor is repaired or replaced.
On Enemies: An enemy's armor, once sundered, remains damaged for all future encounters.
On Players: Damaged player armor can be repaired in two ways:
Blacksmith Repair: A blacksmith can restore the armor to its original full DR for a cost determined by the GM.
Field Repair: During a Short Rest, a character may perform a field repair. This restores the item's DR to a maximum of 2. If the armor's original DR was less than 2, it is restored to its original value.

Dodge (Minor Action): You can spend 2 FP to focus on evasion. The next enemy that attacks you this round does so with Disadvantage (they roll two dice and take the worse result).
Shield Bash (Major Action): If you have a shield, you can spend 2 FP and make a Might roll. If you succeed, your target is staggered and loses their next Major Action.
Shield Counter (Reaction): Requires Bracing. When hit by melee, spend 2 FP and roll Might. On success, target is Exposed (Advantage on next hit against them).


Shield Mastery
Shields offer more than just protection; they are tools for controlling the flow of battle. These actions require a shield.
1. Shield Bash (Major Action + 2 FP)
Use this to stop an enemy's momentum.
The Action: You trade your attack to slam the edge of your shield into the enemy.
The Roll: Standard Might check.
Success: The target is Staggered (Loses their next Major Action).
Tactical Use: This is a 1-for-1 trade. You sacrifice your damage to prevent a Boss from casting a spell or landing a Power Attack.
2. Shield Counter (Reaction + 2 FP)
Use this to create an opening for your allies.
Condition: You must be actively Bracing (using your Minor Action).
Trigger: When a melee attack hits your shield.
The Roll: Standard Might check.
Success: You catch the blow and knock the enemy's guard wide open. The target is Exposed (The next melee attack against them has Advantage).
Tactical Use: This rewards defensive play. By holding the line, you set up your rogue or warrior to land a devastating strike on their turn.
Resistance Rolls: Some spells and abilities inflict a status effect rather than dealing direct damage. When a character successfully uses such an ability, the target must often resist it. This is resolved with a Resistance Roll. The target (whether player or enemy) rolls a d20 against one of their own Stat Scores, as specified by the ability. If they roll equal to or under their Stat, they resist. If they roll over, they suffer the full effect.
The Rules of Engagement
Combat in Skyrim is sticky and dangerous. Once you are within melee reach (5 feet) of an enemy, you are Engaged. You cannot simply walk away without consequence.
Leaving Combat (Disengaging)
To move away from an Engaged enemy, you must use your Minor Action to Move. However, the enemy will try to stop you. You have two choices:
1. The Reckless Retreat
The Action: You simply turn and run using your Minor Action. You save your Major Action for attacking or healing.
The Cost: You lower your guard. The enemy gets a Free Attack against you immediately. (The GM rolls to hit; if successful, you take damage as you leave).
2. The Tactical Withdrawal
You spend your Major Action to force an opening. Choose one of the methods below. You must succeed on the roll to move safely.
Failure: If you fail the roll, you fail to create space. You still use your Minor Action to move away, but you Take the Free Attack as you leave.
The Shove (Might): You use brute force to throw the enemy back.
Roll: Standard Might.
Success Effect: You take no damage. The enemy is Pushed 5 feet directly away from you. This clears the space for you to move or for an ally to step in.


The Slip (Agility): You duck under a blade or roll past a guard.
Roll: Standard Agility.
Success Effect: You take no damage. You may move through the enemy's space if necessary to escape.


The Feint (Guile): You trick the enemy into blocking the wrong way.
Roll: Standard Guile.
Success Effect: You take no damage. The enemy is momentarily confused and cannot take Reactions until the start of their next turn.


Sunder Armor (Melee Only)
Breaking armor requires leverage and physical force. Sunder Armor is a Major Action that can only be performed with a Melee Weapon while Engaged with the target. Archers and Mages must rely on their own methods to bypass defenses.

Archery: The Called Shot
Requires a Bow or Crossbow.
Ranged combat is about precision. When making a ranged attack as your Major Action, you may declare a Called Shot. This applies a penalty to your Agility Target Number (making the shot harder) in exchange for a specific effect. You must declare the shot before rolling.
